Intuition
To check if a string is a palindrome while ignoring non-alphanumeric characters and case, we can first clean the string (keep only letters/digits), convert it to lowercase, and then compare characters from both ends using two pointers.

Approach
Remove all non-alphanumeric characters using regex: replaceAll("[^A-Za-z0-9]", "").

Convert the cleaned string to lowercase to make comparison case-insensitive.

Use two pointers:

i starts from the beginning

j starts from the end

While i < j, compare ss.charAt(i) and ss.charAt(j):

If they differ, it’s not a palindrome → return false.

Otherwise, move pointers inward (i++, j--).

If all pairs match, return true.

Complexity
Time complexity:

𝑂(𝑛) cleaning + one pass comparison.

Space complexity:
O(n) we create a cleaned lowercase string.

Code
class Solution {
    public boolean isPalindrome(String s) {
        
        String input = s.replaceAll("[^A-Za-z0-9]","");
        String ss= input.toLowerCase();
        int i=0;
        int j=input.length()-1;
        boolean isPalindrome=true;
        while(i<j){
            if(ss.charAt(j)!=ss.charAt(i)){
                isPalindrome= false;
                break;
            }
            i++;
            --j;
        }
            return isPalindrome;
        }
        
    }
